Fantasy Football Analysis¶

By: Andrew Yang, Megan Yu, and Frank Deegbe

Motivation¶

For decades fantasy football has dominated the landscape of sports betting by striking a perfect balance between strategy, competition, and luck. It is a online game where participants can create their own football teams by selecting real life NFL players. Each participant, known as a manager, can draft these players from across the league, who will then earn points based on their real world game statistics every week.

Although managers can continue to make changes to their team after the season starts, one of the most pivotal moments of the game is the draft, where players generally select 16 players onto their initial roster in a snake draft. Over the years, many different strategies for drafting have emerged, such as waiting on a quarterback (QB), drafting runningbacks (RB) and wide receivers (WR) in the earlier rounds, or waiting on a runningback to ensure the top talent in other positions.

Having a good draft has significant implications for the season overall. A manager is able to accept a player drafted late to underproduce, as the draft capital for the player is not very high and could easily be cut for free agents. However, if a player drafted within the early rounds (Rounds 1-6) underproduces, it causes significant turmoil since the manager spent a high capital for the player and would not get equivalent return value for trading the player. On the other hand, drafting a sleeper player in the later rounds that massively overproduces becomes a valuable asset and is a critical piece of championship teams, as the overall strength of a manager's team is improved with the same draft cost in relation to the other teams.

A good draft strategy thus looks to minimize the risk of players within the early rounds, while is also good at finding the specific sleepers in the later rounds.

Additional resources can be found here

  • [https://www.espn.com/fantasy/football/story/_/id/34389554/fantasy-football-beginners-how-play-fantasy-football-2022]
  • [https://www.espn.com/fantasy/football/story/_/id/39266124/2024-fantasy-football-draft-rankings-strategy-2023-takeaways]
  • [https://www.si.com/fantasy/top-10-fantasy-football-rookies-nfl-draft-2024-01hxs07j8ck3]
  • [https://www.rotoballer.com/rb-dead-zone-what-is-it-and-do-you-really-need-to-avoid-it/1192614]
  • [https://draftwizard.fantasypros.com/football/mock-draft-simulator/settings/]
  • [https://www.rotoballer.com/fantasy-football-teams-in-a-vacuum/1164424]

Based on the resources above, we have found the following questions to answer in order to determine the players strategy at a particular round.

  • Does the runningback dead zone exist?
  • Is drafting a quarterback or tight end within the first 3 rounds worth the investment?
  • Which position has the most amount of sleepers?
  • Can we predict how well a quarterback will do based on their volume metrics?

The objective of this project is to use statistics and data science to answer the questions above. We hope that through this tutorial, the reader will gain a better understanding of the various draft strategies used in fantasy football as well as better understand how concepts within data science can more accurately model the performance of NFL players.

Procedure¶

We will be using the following datasets

  • NFL-Season-DATA dataset.
  • Average-Draft-Positions dataset.

Each dataset contains statistics of NFL players dating back to 2015, with the first dataset detailing their in season performance and the second dataset containing their average draft positions on various fantasy football platforms.

We will track the following seasons: 2020, 2021, 2022, 2023, combining the two datasets together for each season.

We will then create 4 different data frames represented for each season. If we need to measure a specific player, we will aggregate the 4 different dataframes together, and we would exclude players who have retired within the time frame (2020-2023), meaning 1st, 2nd, and 3rd year players would be included.

Part 1: Data Collection¶

A. Get NFL-Data¶

About our first data set:

  • Our data is extracted from Fantasy.NFL.com divided by season and player position, along with weekly numbers.

  • The extract goes back to the 2015 season as that is the first available season with a full dataset for all positions.

  • Point total and player-ranks are specific for the MML leagues point system but all outer data are raw and can be used for other calculations and simulations.

  • All data are available in comma-separated csv files or row-divided JSON.

During this project, we will be using Python language, and we use tools such as VS Code and Jupiter Notebook to develop this project.

B. Get Average Draft Positions (ADP) Rankings Data¶

Now, onto our second data set. From fantasypros website, we get the Average Draft Position (ADP) for all players in years 2020-2023.

We drop all the irrelevant columns to only keep name (Player), position (POS), and average ADP (AVG).

Some players names have Jr, Jr., Sr, or Sr. at the end. Sometimes one database will include the suffix while another will not. Moreover, the suffix may or may not have a period. This poses a problem because we need to merge databases together by name. Since there is so much variability, we decided to remove these suffixes from all names if it exists. We do so with regex.

The first five rows of the 2023 ADP rankings are displayed below as an example.

In [ ]:
# array of dataframes containing Overall ADP data for years 2020-2023
adp_overall_dfs = []

# we only need the AVG ADP column, so we can drop all others
columns_to_drop = ['Rank', 'Team', 'Bye', 'ESPN', 'Sleeper', 'NFL', 'RTSports', 'FFC']

for year in years:
    # read csv data from csv files in our Data folder
    path = "./Data/FantasyPros_" + year + "_Overall_ADP_Rankings.csv"
    df = pd.read_csv(path)
    df.drop(columns=columns_to_drop, axis=1, inplace=True)
    # remove jr
    df['Player'] = df['Player'].str.replace(r'\s+(Jr|Sr)\.?$', '', regex=True)
    adp_overall_dfs.append(df)

    # Fill N/A values with an empty string
    df['POS'] = df['POS'].fillna('')

Part 2: Data Processing¶

We'll merge the NFL-Data and ADP data dataframes together by player name. We do a left merge, essentially adding ADP ranking to our dataframe of all NFL-Data. Once it's merged together, we drop the repeated Player name column, since it's now in there twice.

Furthermore, we will add one more column to the dataset, which contains the average round in which the running backs are drafted in. We calculate this with by dividing the average draft position (ADP) by 12 (the standard league size). This will come in useful during our exploratory data analysis.

Here is a function that completes this merge and adds the new column:

In [ ]:
# params: list of nfl data dfs, list of adp data dfs
# returns merged df
def merge_dfs(nfl_df_lst, adp_df_list):
    # iterate through years
    for i in range(4):
        nfl_df_lst[i] = pd.merge(nfl_df_lst[i], adp_df_list[i], how="left", left_on="PlayerName", right_on="Player")
        # drop repeat player name column
        nfl_df_lst[i].drop(columns=['Player'], axis=1, inplace=True)
        # we take the floor to have a whole number
        nfl_df_lst[i]['RoundDrafted'] = np.floor(nfl_df_lst[i]['AVG'] / 12) + 1
        
    return nfl_df_lst

Total points vs Round drafted, all positions, all years¶

We will plot the ADP (avg draft position) of players across positions against their total points to see if people are actually drafting the best players first. Our first plot will have data from all four years for all positions.

In general, our data fits the shape of a triangle in the lower left corner of the graph. So we can say that the players who score the most points tend to be drafted the earliest. It's infrequent that high scoring players are drafted in later rounds, but it does happen occasionally, such as the QB drafted in round 25 that scored ~325 points.

However, our data is not linear, as one might expect it to be. There are plenty of players who are drafted early but do not score many points. These players dominate the bottom left corner of our graph.

QBs tend to score the most points, then WRs, then RBs, then TEs. They are not all in the same range. We will analyze each position further.

Avg total points vs round drafted, all years, for each position¶

Let's first find the average number of points that are scored by a specific position in a specific round.

We first begin by finding the average amount of points a QB, RB, WR, and TE will score if they are drafted in a specific round. We do this by aggregating the sum of all the points scored by that specific position over 2020-2023, and divide it by that many occurances. Historically, there are only 16-17 fantasy draft rounds unless the league is very large, so we standardized a cutoff for the draft at round 20 to account for additional margins.

In [ ]:
# create a 2x2 plot of subplots
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(10,8))

# so we can iterate through each position
all_position_dfs = [rb_dfs, qb_dfs, wr_dfs, te_dfs]
all_position_names = ['Running backs', 'Quarter backs', 'Wide receivers', 'Tight ends']

# Store the keys for the dictionary
all_position_abbr = ['RB', 'QB', 'WR', 'TE']

# Dictionary to store the average points per round for each position
average_points_dict = {abbr: [] for abbr in all_position_abbr}

# pos_i is position index, year_i is year index
for pos_i, ax in enumerate(axs.flat):
    total_points_per_round = np.zeros(20)
    counts_per_round = np.zeros(20)
    
    for year_i in range(4):
        # Filter data for rounds 1 to 20
        data = all_position_dfs[pos_i][year_i][all_position_dfs[pos_i][year_i]["RoundDrafted"] <= 20]
        
        # Sum total points and count occurrences for each round
        for round_num in range(1, 21):
            round_data = data[data["RoundDrafted"] == round_num]
            total_points_per_round[round_num-1] += round_data["TotalPoints"].sum()
            counts_per_round[round_num-1] += len(round_data)
    
    # Calculate the average total points for each round
    average_points_per_round_all = np.divide(total_points_per_round, counts_per_round, out=np.zeros_like(total_points_per_round), where=counts_per_round != 0)
    
    # Save the average points per round for the current position in the dictionary
    average_points_dict[all_position_abbr[pos_i]] = average_points_per_round_all.tolist()
    
    
    # Plot the average total points as a bar chart
    ax.bar(np.arange(1, 21), average_points_per_round_all, alpha=0.7)
    
    ax.set_title(all_position_names[pos_i])
    ax.set_xlim(0.5, 20.5)
    ax.set_ylim(0, 400)

# overall title
fig.suptitle('Total Points vs Round Drafted', fontsize=16)

# Add shared x and y labels
fig.text(0.5, 0.01, 'Round drafted', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=14)
fig.text(0.01, 0.5, 'Avg Total points', ha='center', va='center', rotation='vertical', fontsize=14)

# increase margins
plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.5, hspace=0.5)

plt.show()

Notice that we created a dictionary to store the average points per round for each position. This will come in handy to answer our first question.

We see that Quarterbacks generally score far more points than runningbacks, wide receivers, and tight ends, and generally scores over 250 fantasy points until round 10.

Notice how no quarterbacks were taken in round 1 and that no tight ends were taken at round 19. Let's make another plot, but only look at the first 7 rounds now and without quarterbacks. We choose to consider the first 7, because the first 7 players are generally the starting line up.

For the smaller sample size, we can see that wide receivers tend to have a gradual decline in production, while runningbacks and tightends appear to have numbers that fluctuate more between each round.

Standardize total points across positions¶

To answer questions like which position ought to be drafted first, we should standardize the datasets for each position. This is so we can make comparisions across positions. For example, we could compare how a good a QB is relative to other QBs with how good a WR is relative to other WRs.

Within each position, we could either standardize data within each year, or across all four years. To decide which option is better, we will make 4 plot of total points vs draft position - one for each position, where the years are distinguished by color. Thus, we can gain a better understanding of how similar trends are in different years as well as how many players within that position are drafted in that specific round.

The distributions are quite different among different positions. For RBs and WRs, there tend to be more players drafted early on that do not score many points. On the other hand, QBs and TEs don't have as many of these early-drafted low-scoring players. This supports our knowledge that people tend to draft RBs and WRs earlier on.

Without doing any calculations, it appears that the variance between the players performance was very large in the first couple of rounds, however it gradually decreased as the rounds increased. Between each year, we see that no one year looks significantly below or above the other years. Thus, we will probably standardize across all four years, instead of just within each year.

Below is a function to add a column that is the standardized total points (over all four years). It takes in a list of dataframes (for different years) for a position.

It returns the updated dataframe.

In [ ]:
def standardize_pos(pos_dfs):
    # take mean and std over all four years
    mean = np.array([pos_df['TotalPoints'].values for pos_df in pos_dfs]).mean()
    std = np.array([pos_df['TotalPoints'].values for pos_df in pos_dfs]).std()
    # for each year, add a column
    for i in range(len(pos_dfs)):
        pos_dfs[i]['TotalPointsStandardized'] = (pos_dfs[i]['TotalPoints'] - mean) / std
    return pos_dfs

We'll call our standardization function on all positions, which are stored in all_position_dfs.

The output is the RB 2023 dataframe, with a new column, TotalPointsStandardized.

for i in range(len(all_position_dfs)):
    all_position_dfs[i] = standardize_pos(all_position_dfs[i])

Part 4: Model: Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, ML¶

Q1: Does the Runningback dead zone exist?¶

The running back dead zone is defined as the space around rounds three to six, where there is a significant drop off in value for the runningbacks available. This is believed to occur because many NFL teams use a running back by committee approach, where 2 or 3 runningbacks will be used in a game. As a result, the points each of them score is expected to be lower.

Many draft strategies have appeared from this belief, such as zero-RB https://www.fantasylife.com/articles/best-ball/what-is-zero-rb-drafting-tips-from-a-pro, where the player does not believe this dead zone exists and only starts to draft RBs after round 4 or 5, and hero-RB https://www.espn.com/fantasy/football/story/_/id/38191251/fantasy-football-mock-draft-strategy-hero-rb-anchor-rb, where the player drafts multiple runningbacks within the first 3 rounds.

To measure if there is a deadzone, we will look at the difference between the average amounts of points a running back scores for each round between 2020 and 2023. If the difference is not linear we can conclude that a drop off does exist. We can use our previous dataframe for the histograms of the average points scored per round. We will look at the change in points between each round of the draft by subtracting the subsequent round's average points by the previous round. If a difference is positive it means that there is a decrease between the rounds while a negative difference means there was an increase.

In [ ]:
average_points_rb = average_points_dict['RB']

Each bar represents the change in points between two rounds. This graph does not appear to be linear, signifying there are instances where there could be a very steep change, or other instances where it stagnates. For example, the drop off in points from round 1 to round 2 is 35.72, while the drop off from round 2 to round 3 is 34.58. However, between round 3 and 4, the average points scored actually increases, and fluctutes. This shows that the drop off in runningback talent is extremely steep, meaning that there is only so many top tier players that by round 3 they are mostly gone, and the players onward are similar level in talent.

Taking the average points per round into context as well, we see that the points hover between 140 to 170 points between rounds 3 and 10. A runningback deadzone very much exists at that range.

Insights¶

Looking at both pieces of data, it does seem to contain a running back deadzone range. There is a steep decline in the production from top tier runningbacks after round two, leading the fluctuations in point differences in the subsequent rounds. However, we found that rather the deadzone range be from rounds 3 to 6, it actually extends up to round 10. This means two things. Firstly, if an owner is prioritizing drafting top tier runningbacks, then drafting one within the first two rounds is essential. However, if an owner misses this cutoff range, then it may be beneficial for him/her to wait on runningbacks until a little later within the deadzone, so that they can prioritize other positions while still receving a similar quality of runningback performance in the later rounds.

Q2: Is drafting a quarterback or tight end within the first 3 rounds worth the investment?¶

Another pattern many managers employ is holding off on drafting a quarterback in the early rounds, believing that there would be significant amounts of high performing quarterbacks in later rounds https://campus2canton.com/breaking-down-the-late-round-qb-cff-draft-strategy/. On the other hand, managers race to draft a top 3 tight end, believing they have a significant drop off as well https://www.draftsharks.com/article/fantasy-football-draft-preview-tight-ends.

We create two hypothesis tests to answer this question.

Test 1

  • H0: The top 3 quarterbacks drafted do not substantially outproduce quarterbacks drafted outside of the top 3
  • H1: The top 3 quarterbacks drafted do substantially outproduce quarterbacks drafted outside of the top 3

Test 2

  • H0: The top 3 tight ends drafted do not substantially outproduce tight ends drafted outside of the top 3
  • H1: The top 3 tight ends drafted do substantially outproduce tight ends drafted outside of the top 3

We can explore both of these hypothesis by creating two categories for each position:

Top 3 Drafted: QBs and TEs drafted within the top 3.

Outside Top 3 Drafted: QBs and TEs drafted outside the top 3.

We can then calculate the mean and standard deviation of our two samples and test our hypotheses.

In [ ]:
top3_means = []
outside_top3_means = []

for df in qb_dfs:
    # Get the mean fantasy points for top 3 and outside top 3
    top3_mean = df[df['Rank'] <= 3]['TotalPoints'].mean()
    outside_top3_mean = df[df['Rank'] > 3]['TotalPoints'].mean()

    # Append the means to the respective lists
    top3_means.append(top3_mean)
    outside_top3_means.append(outside_top3_mean)

# Convert lists to pandas Series for easier statistical analysis
top3_series = pd.Series(top3_means, index=[2020, 2021, 2022, 2023])
outside_top3_series = pd.Series(outside_top3_means, index=[2020, 2021, 2022, 2023])

# Perform normality test
top3_normality = stats.shapiro(top3_series)
outside_top3_normality = stats.shapiro(outside_top3_series)

if top3_normality.pvalue > 0.05 and outside_top3_normality.pvalue > 0.05:
    t_test_result = stats.ttest_ind(top3_series, outside_top3_series)
else:
    t_test_result = stats.mannwhitneyu(top3_series, outside_top3_series)

Interpertation¶

QBs

From the result of our T-test, we can observe a t-value of 10.75. This indicates that there is a significant difference between the means of the top 3 drafted QB's and the rest of the dataset. Alternatively, the difference would be over 10 times the standard error. This finding is augmented by the low p-value (0.0000382).

To conclude, We are able to reject the Null Hypothesis, H0 (The top 3 quarterbacks drafted do not substantially outproduce quarterbacks drafted outside of the top 3) in support for the alternative hypothesis H1 (The top 3 quarterbacks drafted do substantially outproduce quarterbacks drafted outside of the top 3)

This suggests the notion that managers should hold off on drafting QBs until the later rounds as the top 3 quarterbacks do not provide substantial value compared to the rest of the pack.

TEs

The Mann-Whitney U test was used instead of the t-test due to the non-normality of the data. The p-value of 0.02857 < 0.05, indicating that we again, reject the null hypothesis, H0 (The top 3 tight ends drafted do not substantially outproduce tight ends drafted outside of the top 3) in favor of the alternative hypothesis H1 (The top 3 tight ends drafted do substantially outproduce tight ends drafted outside of the top 3)

This suggests that while the previous notion is unfounded, managers should not completely disregard drafting a top TE if there is good value.

Additonally, we can calculate the difference between the means to determine which one should be valued more.

Q3: Which position has the greatest probability of producing breakout players?¶

Every fantasy manager wants to find a breakout player, a player that ends up significantly outperforming their expected performance. This player can be defined as the following, players who were unknown to the league or players who were once very productive but has since been underperforming. We will examine the performance of each position relative to the performance of other players in that position to determine if they can be considered a breakout player or sleeper pick. For more information on sleepers and current sleeper picks for this year, see [https://www.draftsharks.com/article/fantasy-football-sleepers]

First, let us use the standardized dataframes.

In order to properly calculate a breakout player, we have to first identify a specific region of the plot that we can consider to be high performing within fantasy. Let us define the top 75th percentile of total points as being fantasy productive. We define this to disregard the cases where a severely low performing fantasy player will outperform expectations, but still not be very productive. For example, the 50th projected ranked runningback could finish the season as the 30th ranked runningback, which would be an outperformance, but it would still not constitute a significant contribution to a team.

Now to determine if a player finished within the top 75th percentile or not, we will check to see if the player was previously under the radar. For this we identified that a player is considered a sleeper if the player was previously ranked 20% or more under his finish percentile (eg. A player projected in the 70th perentile that finishes in the 97th percentile is a sleeper).

We first create the dataframe to store just the projected rankings and the season performance standardized.

Now let's determine the percentiles for the position ranking before the season and then standardized points after the season. We will use the scipy.stats library for that. Let us also create a function for that. We also need to handle the case where there are NaN values in POS, we can just use a large number for those cases.

In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import percentileofscore
In [ ]:

wr_projected_and_season_percentiles = []
te_projected_and_season_percentiles = []
qb_projected_and_season_percentiles = []

Let's now find the percentiles.

In [ ]:
def calculate_percentiles(dfs):
    filtered_dfs = []
    for df in dfs:
        columns = df[["POS", "TotalPointsStandardized"]].copy()
        
        # Replace NaN values in 'POS' with a high number
        columns.fillna({'POS' : 99999}, inplace=True)
        columns['POS'] = columns['POS'].astype(str)
        
        # Calculate rank for TotalPointsStandardized
        columns['PositionRank'] = columns['TotalPointsStandardized'].rank(ascending=False)
        
        # Calculate percentiles for TotalPointsStandardized
        columns['TotalPointsPercentile'] = columns['TotalPointsStandardized'].apply(
            lambda x: percentileofscore(columns['TotalPointsStandardized'], x)
        )

        # Calculate percentiles for POS. We use 100 - percentile to signify 
        # that a lower number means the player is ranked higher, and thus in a higher percentile.
        columns['POSPercentile'] = columns['POS'].apply(
            lambda x: 100 - percentileofscore(columns['POS'], x)
        )

        filtered_dfs.append(columns)
    return filtered_dfs

rb_projected_and_season_percentiles = calculate_percentiles(rb_dfs)
wr_projected_and_season_percentiles = calculate_percentiles(wr_dfs)
te_projected_and_season_percentiles = calculate_percentiles(te_dfs)
qb_projected_and_season_percentiles = calculate_percentiles(qb_dfs)

Now, let's determine how many players were breakout players by creating a function to calculate that.

In [ ]:
top_70_percentile = 70
percentile_difference = 20

def calculate_breakout_number(dfs, breakout_count):
    for df in dfs:
        for index, row in df.iterrows():
            if row['TotalPointsPercentile'] >= top_70_percentile and (row['TotalPointsPercentile'] - row['POSPercentile']) >= 20:
                breakout_count += 1
    return breakout_count

Insights¶

Based on our results, it seems that runningbacks contain the most breakout players in a season, followed by wide receivers, then tight ends, and lastly quarterbacks. This lines up with our findings earlier about the runningback dead zone, since the runningback points remained consistent between rounds 3 and 10, meaning that some of the running backs towards later rounds could be classified as breakout players in this scenario.

This showcases that contrary to the belief that runningbacks in the later rounds could not be classified as productive, there is still a plethora of talent available. Rather, the data suggests that quarterbacks and tightends may be less volatile, and generally fit more closely to their previous rankings. Consequently, a manager may want to wait until the middle rounds (4-7) to draft a quarterback or tightend, since the chances of a breakout are lower. In order to maximize the chances of drafting a breakout player, managers should target runningbacks and receviers in the later rounds (9+).

Q4: Can we predict how well a quarterback will do based on their volume metrics?¶

Our first three questions attempted to answer some of the biggest questions regarding which position of players to target, but now that we have decided on a specific position, what players are best to draft for that position? Thus we are attempting to ask how does the amount of attempts to score points (volume) impact fantasy success for Quarterbacks.

Total points is calculated off of some metrics, such as yards, touchdowns, and receptions, but disregards other metrics, such as touches, targets, and red zone statistics. We will see if these unused metrics can predict what percentile a player will end up being relative to all other players of their position. You can read more on how fantasy points are calculated here https://fantasydata.com/api/fantasy-scoring-system/nfl.

Focusing on quarterbacks, We will attempt to fit a regression line to predict the total points generated by the player, and analyze the mean squared error, along with with the weights to determine how well it did.

We will be using the following statistics as our weights: Touch Carries, Touch Receptions, Touches, Targets Receptions, Reception Percentage, Red Zone Target, Red Zone Touches, Red Zone Goal to Goal, and Total Points.

The Redzone is classified as the area of the field between the 20 yard line and the endzone, while ReadZoneG2G is between the 10 yard line and the endzone.

For quarterbacks more specifically, since they don't often catch the ball, only Touches, Redzone Touches, and Red Zone Goal to Goal Touches are significant. We will attempt to see how accurate they are in determining a players fantasy performance.

Due to data being missing at random (MAR), and many players not getting to play each season, we will fill the missing data in as 0's, add only the touch statistics, in addition to the regular point calculation.

In [ ]:
def merge_and_clean(dataframe_list):
    """
    Merges a list of DataFrames into a single DataFrame and drops columns unrelated to
    the calculation of fantasy football points, except for columns related to touches.

    Parameters:
    dataframe_list (list of pd.DataFrame): List of DataFrames to merge and filter

    Returns:
    pd.DataFrame: A single merged and filtered DataFrame
    """
    # Concatenate the list of DataFrames
    concatenated_df = pd.concat(dataframe_list, ignore_index=True)

    # Define columns to keep
    columns_to_keep = [
        'PassingYDS', 'PassingTD', 'PassingInt',
        'RushingYDS', 'RushingTD',
        'ReceivingRec', 'ReceivingYDS', 'ReceivingTD',
        'RetTD', 'FumTD', '2PT', 'Fum',
        'FanPtsAgainst-pts', 'TouchCarries', 'TouchReceptions', 'Touches',
        'TargetsReceptions', 'Targets', 'ReceptionPercentage',
        'RzTarget', 'RzTouch', 'RzG2G', 'TotalPoints'
    ]

    # Filter the DataFrame to keep only the necessary columns
    filtered_df = concatenated_df[columns_to_keep]
    filtered_df = filtered_df.fillna(0)

    return filtered_df

Interpretation¶

Now, we can conclude that our neural network preforms worse than our fitted linear regresson line. This can be due to overfitting, where the neural network captures too much noise from the training data that do not generalize well to new, unseen data. The linear regression model, being simpler, may generalize better if the underlying relationship between the features and the target variable is approximately linear. Additionally, there may have not been enough data to allow the neural network to preform at optimal efficency.

What does this mean for fantasy?¶

Regardless of specific model we use, we still arrive at a low mean squared error. This means that Redzone Touches, Redzone Touches inside the 10 yard line, and Overall touches are a strong predictor for fantasy performance.

Our results corroborate with this article on how "volume is king", explaining how for various positions that opportunties to score will lead to more fantasy points.

https://www.espn.com/fantasy/football/story/_/id/38069858/fantasy-football-statistics-targets-trends

For the manager, it would be ideal to draft a quarterback that they anticipate would drive down the field more and get into the redzone, so that they could have more opportunities to score touchdowns and fantasy points.

Part 5: Interpretation / Insight¶

Based on the 4 Questions that we asked, these are our following insights and answers.

  1. Does the runningback dead zone exist?

The runningback dead zone does exist between rounds 3-10. The draft strategy accordingly should be users should target runningbacks in rounds 1 and 2, but hold off on drafting them until rounds 7-10 to still reap similar production to RBs selected earlier in the deadzone.

  1. Is drafting a quarterback or tight end within the first 3 rounds worth the investment?

Neither is drafting a top 3 quarterback or tight end worth the initial investment. However between the two, it is more worth it to draft a top 3 quarterback over a top 3 tight end. Ideally, both positions could be held off on drafting until the mid rounds.

  1. Which position has the most amount of sleepers?

From most to least: Runningbacks, Wide Receivers, Tight Ends, Quarterbacks. A late round draft strategy should include primarily of RBs and WRs.

  1. Can we predict how well a quarterback will do based on their volume metrics?

Volume metrics such as Redzone Touches and Overall touches are fairly accurate towards predicting fantasy Quarterback success. As a result, players to anticipate drafting Quarterbacks they believe can easily pass the ball down the field to and get inside the RedZone.
